00:08:03.266 --> 00:08:07.706 A:middle
So, what if the only gestures

00:08:07.706 --> 00:08:09.246 A:middle
you could do was this horizontal

00:08:09.246 --> 00:08:11.226 A:middle
gesture between apps, and then a

00:08:11.226 --> 00:08:12.666 A:middle
vertical gesture to go home, and

00:08:12.666 --> 00:08:13.256 A:middle
that's it.

00:08:13.256 --> 00:08:14.316 A:middle
You couldn't do any of that

00:08:14.316 --> 00:08:15.416 A:middle
in-between stuff I just

00:08:15.416 --> 00:08:15.776 A:middle
mentioned.

00:08:16.636 --> 00:08:17.846 A:middle
Well, what would happen is that

00:08:17.846 --> 00:08:19.406 A:middle
you would have to think before

00:08:19.696 --> 00:08:21.136 A:middle
what you did, before you

00:08:21.136 --> 00:08:21.876 A:middle
performed the gesture, you'd

00:08:21.876 --> 00:08:23.086 A:middle
have to think what you want to

00:08:23.086 --> 00:08:23.153 A:middle
do.

00:08:23.986 --> 00:08:25.156 A:middle
And so, the series of events

00:08:25.156 --> 00:08:26.276 A:middle
would be very linear, right?

00:08:26.316 --> 00:08:27.276 A:middle
So, you'd have to think, do I

00:08:27.276 --> 00:08:28.106 A:middle
want to go home?

00:08:28.106 --> 00:08:29.396 A:middle
Do I want to go to multitasking?

00:08:29.826 --> 00:08:30.876 A:middle
Then you make your decision,

00:08:30.876 --> 00:08:32.306 A:middle
then you perform the gesture,

00:08:32.306 --> 00:08:32.905 A:middle
and then you release.

00:08:34.206 --> 00:08:35.876 A:middle
But, the cool thing is when it's

00:08:35.956 --> 00:08:37.876 A:middle
redirectable, the thought and

00:08:37.876 --> 00:08:39.746 A:middle
gesture happen in parallel.

00:08:40.426 --> 00:08:42.535 A:middle
And, you sort of think it with

00:08:42.635 --> 00:08:44.756 A:middle
the gesture, and it turns out

00:08:44.756 --> 00:08:46.776 A:middle
this is way faster than thinking

00:08:46.776 --> 00:08:47.386 A:middle
before doing.

00:08:47.386 --> 00:08:48.826 A:middle
You know? Because it's a

00:08:48.856 --> 00:08:52.326 A:middle
multi-axis gestural space.

00:08:52.326 --> 00:08:53.676 A:middle
It's not separate gestures.

00:08:53.986 --> 00:08:55.616 A:middle
It's one gesture that does all

00:08:55.616 --> 00:08:55.976 A:middle
this stuff.

00:08:55.976 --> 00:08:57.306 A:middle
Home, multitasking, quick app

00:08:57.306 --> 00:08:58.266 A:middle
switching, so you don't have to

00:08:58.646 --> 00:08:59.766 A:middle
think about it as a separate

00:08:59.766 --> 00:09:00.166 A:middle
gesture.

00:08:59.766 --> 00:09:00.166 A:middle
gesture.

00:09:01.206 --> 00:09:03.796 A:middle
And, helps with discovery.

00:09:03.916 --> 00:09:05.346 A:middle
Because you can discover a new

00:09:05.346 --> 00:09:06.776 A:middle
gesture along the path of an

00:09:06.776 --> 00:09:07.656 A:middle
existing gesture.

00:09:08.546 --> 00:09:10.886 A:middle
And, it allows you to layer

00:09:10.886 --> 00:09:11.956 A:middle
gestures at the speed of

00:09:12.046 --> 00:09:12.706 A:middle
thought.

00:09:13.256 --> 00:09:14.156 A:middle
So, what does that last one

00:09:14.156 --> 00:09:14.286 A:middle
mean?

00:09:14.896 --> 00:09:15.986 A:middle
So, let me show you some

00:09:15.986 --> 00:09:16.566 A:middle
examples.

00:09:16.826 --> 00:09:17.846 A:middle
And, we've slowed down the

00:09:17.846 --> 00:09:19.196 A:middle
physics on the simulation, so

00:09:19.196 --> 00:09:20.626 A:middle
you can actually see a little

00:09:20.626 --> 00:09:21.616 A:middle
bit what I'm talking about.

00:09:22.506 --> 00:09:26.006 A:middle
So, I can swipe to go home, and

00:09:26.006 --> 00:09:27.566 A:middle
then swipe to the next page, or

00:09:27.566 --> 00:09:28.946 A:middle
springboard while I'm going

00:09:28.946 --> 00:09:29.176 A:middle
home.

00:09:29.176 --> 00:09:30.616 A:middle
I can layer these two gestures

00:09:30.616 --> 00:09:31.806 A:middle
once I've internalized them.

00:09:33.186 --> 00:09:34.796 A:middle
Another example is that I can

00:09:34.796 --> 00:09:35.846 A:middle
launch an app and realize, oh,

00:09:35.846 --> 00:09:37.126 A:middle
actually I need to go to

00:09:37.126 --> 00:09:38.186 A:middle
multitasking, and I can

00:09:38.316 --> 00:09:39.806 A:middle
interrupt the app and go

00:09:39.806 --> 00:09:41.396 A:middle
straight to multitasking, while

00:09:41.396 --> 00:09:42.256 A:middle
the app is launching.

00:09:43.566 --> 00:09:47.296 A:middle
Or, I can launch an app and

00:09:47.296 --> 00:09:49.016 A:middle
realize, oh, that was the wrong

00:09:49.016 --> 00:09:49.136 A:middle
app.

00:09:49.846 --> 00:09:51.096 A:middle
And, I can shoot it back home,

00:09:51.246 --> 00:09:53.066 A:middle
while I'm launching it.

00:09:53.756 --> 00:09:56.406 A:middle
Now, there's one other one where

00:09:56.406 --> 00:09:58.516 A:middle
I can actually just launch an

00:09:58.516 --> 00:10:00.166 A:middle
app, and if I'm in a hurry, I

00:09:58.516 --> 00:10:00.166 A:middle
app, and if I'm in a hurry, I

00:10:00.166 --> 00:10:01.256 A:middle
can start interacting with the

00:10:01.256 --> 00:10:01.976 A:middle
app as it's launching.

00:10:03.436 --> 00:10:05.366 A:middle
So, this stuff might not seem

00:10:05.366 --> 00:10:06.766 A:middle
really important, but we've

00:10:06.876 --> 00:10:08.256 A:middle
found it's super important for

00:10:08.256 --> 00:10:09.786 A:middle
the interface to be always

00:10:09.786 --> 00:10:11.426 A:middle
responding, always understanding

00:10:11.426 --> 00:10:11.576 A:middle
you.

00:10:12.006 --> 00:10:13.566 A:middle
It always feels alive.

00:10:13.566 --> 00:10:16.306 A:middle
And, that's really important for

00:10:16.306 --> 00:10:17.416 A:middle
your expectation and

00:10:17.416 --> 00:10:18.776 A:middle
understanding of the interface,

00:10:19.196 --> 00:10:20.396 A:middle
to be comfortable with it.

00:10:20.716 --> 00:10:21.736 A:middle
To realize that it's always

00:10:21.776 --> 00:10:22.766 A:middle
going to respond to you when you

00:10:22.766 --> 00:10:23.436 A:middle
need it.

00:10:23.966 --> 00:10:27.776 A:middle
And, that applies as well to

00:10:27.776 --> 00:10:29.476 A:middle
changes in motion, not just to

00:10:29.756 --> 00:10:31.496 A:middle
the start of an interaction, but

00:10:31.496 --> 00:10:32.796 A:middle
when you're in the middle of an

00:10:32.796 --> 00:10:33.526 A:middle
interaction, and you're

00:10:33.526 --> 00:10:34.106 A:middle
changing.

00:10:34.666 --> 00:10:35.726 A:middle
It's important for us to be

00:10:35.726 --> 00:10:37.196 A:middle
responsive to interruption as

00:10:37.196 --> 00:10:37.486 A:middle
well.

00:10:38.046 --> 00:10:39.236 A:middle
So, a good example is

00:10:39.236 --> 00:10:40.606 A:middle
multitasking on iPhone 10.

00:10:41.456 --> 00:10:42.936 A:middle
So, we have this pause gesture

00:10:42.936 --> 00:10:44.136 A:middle
where you slide your finger up

00:10:44.136 --> 00:10:45.506 A:middle
halfway up the screen, and

00:10:45.506 --> 00:10:47.726 A:middle
pause, and so we need to figure

00:10:47.726 --> 00:10:50.506 A:middle
out how to detect this change in

00:10:50.506 --> 00:10:50.896 A:middle
motion.

00:10:50.896 --> 00:10:52.166 A:middle
And so, how do we do this?

00:10:52.166 --> 00:10:53.216 A:middle
How do we detect this change in

00:10:53.216 --> 00:10:53.576 A:middle
motion?

00:10:53.956 --> 00:10:55.036 A:middle
Should we use a timer?

00:10:55.306 --> 00:10:56.586 A:middle
Should we wait until your finger

00:10:56.586 --> 00:10:57.756 A:middle
has come below a certain

00:10:57.756 --> 00:10:59.486 A:middle
velocity for a few amount of

00:10:59.536 --> 00:11:01.836 A:middle
time, and then [inaudible] bring

00:10:59.536 --> 00:11:01.836 A:middle
time, and then [inaudible] bring

00:11:01.836 --> 00:11:02.886 A:middle
in the multitasking cards?

00:11:02.886 --> 00:11:04.236 A:middle
Well, it turns out that's too

00:11:04.236 --> 00:11:04.976 A:middle
slow.

00:11:05.196 --> 00:11:06.636 A:middle
People expect to be able to get

00:11:06.636 --> 00:11:08.086 A:middle
to multitasking instantly.

00:11:08.786 --> 00:11:10.856 A:middle
And, we need a way that can

00:11:10.856 --> 00:11:13.986 A:middle
respond as fast as them.

00:11:14.206 --> 00:11:15.116 A:middle
So, instead we look at your

00:11:15.116 --> 00:11:16.376 A:middle
finger's acceleration.

00:11:17.266 --> 00:11:18.636 A:middle
It turns out there's a huge

00:11:18.636 --> 00:11:20.336 A:middle
spike in the acceleration of

00:11:20.336 --> 00:11:21.416 A:middle
your finger when you pause.

00:11:21.816 --> 00:11:23.056 A:middle
And, actually the faster you

00:11:23.056 --> 00:11:25.076 A:middle
stop, the faster we can detect

00:11:25.076 --> 00:11:25.226 A:middle
it.

00:11:25.776 --> 00:11:27.016 A:middle
So, it's actually responding to

00:11:27.016 --> 00:11:29.126 A:middle
the change in motion, as fast as

00:11:29.126 --> 00:11:30.886 A:middle
we know how, instead of waiting

00:11:30.886 --> 00:11:31.676 A:middle
for some timer.

00:11:33.006 --> 00:11:34.326 A:middle
So, this is a good example of

00:11:34.326 --> 00:11:35.666 A:middle
responding to redirection as

00:11:35.666 --> 00:11:37.006 A:middle
fast as possible.

00:11:37.586 --> 00:11:40.856 A:middle
So, this is the concept of

00:11:41.196 --> 00:11:42.436 A:middle
interruption and redirection.

00:11:43.096 --> 00:11:44.426 A:middle
This stuff makes the interface

00:11:44.426 --> 00:11:45.936 A:middle
feel really, really connected to

00:11:46.046 --> 00:11:46.246 A:middle
you.

00:11:47.596 --> 00:11:50.576 A:middle
Next, we want to talk a little

00:11:50.576 --> 00:11:51.646 A:middle
bit about the architecture of

00:11:51.646 --> 00:11:52.096 A:middle
the interface.

00:11:52.096 --> 00:11:52.976 A:middle
How you lay it out,

00:11:53.716 --> 00:11:54.406 A:middle
conceptually.

00:11:55.696 --> 00:11:56.596 A:middle
And, we think when you're doing

00:11:56.596 --> 00:11:58.006 A:middle
that, it's important to maintain

00:11:58.116 --> 00:11:59.846 A:middle
spatial consistency throughout

00:11:59.956 --> 00:12:00.246 A:middle
movement.

00:11:59.956 --> 00:12:00.246 A:middle
movement.

00:12:01.126 --> 00:12:01.686 A:middle
What does that mean?

00:12:02.526 --> 00:12:03.716 A:middle
This kind of mimics the way our

00:12:03.766 --> 00:12:05.656 A:middle
object persistence memory works

00:12:05.806 --> 00:12:06.436 A:middle
in the real world.

00:12:07.116 --> 00:12:08.766 A:middle
So, things smoothly leave and

00:12:08.766 --> 00:12:09.756 A:middle
enter our perception in

00:12:09.866 --> 00:12:10.426 A:middle
symmetric paths.

00:12:11.866 --> 00:12:13.246 A:middle
So, if something disappears one

00:12:13.246 --> 00:12:15.556 A:middle
way, we expect it to emerge from

00:12:15.556 --> 00:12:16.146 A:middle
where it came?

00:12:16.306 --> 00:12:18.056 A:middle
Right? So, if I walked off this

00:12:18.056 --> 00:12:20.006 A:middle
stage this way, and then emerged

00:12:20.136 --> 00:12:21.836 A:middle
that way, you'd be pretty

00:12:21.836 --> 00:12:22.496 A:middle
amazed, right?

00:12:22.846 --> 00:12:24.776 A:middle
Because that's impossible.

00:12:25.486 --> 00:12:27.256 A:middle
So, we wanted to play into this

00:12:27.736 --> 00:12:29.516 A:middle
consistent sense of space that

00:12:29.516 --> 00:12:31.246 A:middle
we all have in the world.

00:12:31.806 --> 00:12:34.776 A:middle
And so, what that means is, if

00:12:34.776 --> 00:12:36.116 A:middle
something is going out of view

00:12:36.116 --> 00:12:37.186 A:middle
in your interface, and coming

00:12:37.186 --> 00:12:39.156 A:middle
back into view, it should do so

00:12:39.156 --> 00:12:40.386 A:middle
in symmetric paths.

00:12:40.796 --> 00:12:42.006 A:middle
It should have a consistent

00:12:42.096 --> 00:12:44.606 A:middle
offscreen path as it enters and

00:12:44.606 --> 00:12:44.836 A:middle
leaves.

00:12:44.836 --> 00:12:45.756 A:middle
A good example of this is

00:12:45.916 --> 00:12:47.246 A:middle
actually iOS navigation.

00:12:47.246 --> 00:12:48.706 A:middle
When I tap on an element in this

00:12:48.706 --> 00:12:50.176 A:middle
list here, it slides in from the

00:12:50.176 --> 00:12:50.406 A:middle
right.

00:12:51.196 --> 00:12:52.636 A:middle
When I tap the back button, it

00:12:52.636 --> 00:12:53.866 A:middle
goes back to the right.

00:12:53.926 --> 00:12:55.656 A:middle
It's a symmetric path.

00:12:55.656 --> 00:12:57.276 A:middle
Each element has a consistent

00:12:57.276 --> 00:12:58.626 A:middle
place where it lives at both

00:12:58.716 --> 00:12:59.286 A:middle
states.

00:12:59.966 --> 00:13:01.296 A:middle
This also reinforces the

00:12:59.966 --> 00:13:01.296 A:middle
This also reinforces the

00:13:01.296 --> 00:13:01.646 A:middle
gesture.

00:13:01.646 --> 00:13:03.336 A:middle
If I choose to slide it myself

00:13:03.416 --> 00:13:04.576 A:middle
to the right, because I know

00:13:04.576 --> 00:13:05.586 A:middle
that's where it lives, I can do

00:13:05.586 --> 00:13:05.786 A:middle
that.

00:13:05.786 --> 00:13:06.466 A:middle
It's expected.

00:13:07.426 --> 00:13:08.686 A:middle
So, what if we didn't do this.

00:13:09.146 --> 00:13:10.236 A:middle
Here's an example, where when I

00:13:10.236 --> 00:13:11.816 A:middle
tap on something, it slides in,

00:13:11.816 --> 00:13:13.926 A:middle
and then when I hit back it goes

00:13:13.926 --> 00:13:14.316 A:middle
down.

00:13:14.316 --> 00:13:15.916 A:middle
And, it feels disconnected and

00:13:15.916 --> 00:13:16.796 A:middle
confusing, right?

00:13:17.476 --> 00:13:18.826 A:middle
It feels like I'm sending it

00:13:19.136 --> 00:13:19.576 A:middle
somewhere.

00:13:19.576 --> 00:13:20.626 A:middle
In fact, if I wanted to

00:13:20.626 --> 00:13:21.736 A:middle
communicate that I was sending

00:13:21.736 --> 00:13:22.746 A:middle
it somewhere, this is how I

00:13:22.746 --> 00:13:23.616 A:middle
could do it, right?

00:13:24.816 --> 00:13:26.496 A:middle
So, that's the topic of spatial

00:13:26.496 --> 00:13:27.246 A:middle
consistency.

00:13:28.056 --> 00:13:29.396 A:middle
It helps the gesture feel

00:13:29.396 --> 00:13:30.736 A:middle
aligned with our spatial

00:13:30.736 --> 00:13:33.796 A:middle
understanding of the world.

00:13:33.796 --> 00:13:36.766 A:middle
Now, the next one is to hint in

00:13:36.766 --> 00:13:37.906 A:middle
the direction of the gesture.

00:13:38.796 --> 00:13:40.216 A:middle
You know, we humans are always,

00:13:40.306 --> 00:13:41.596 A:middle
kind of, predicting the next few

00:13:41.596 --> 00:13:43.356 A:middle
steps of our experience.

00:13:43.746 --> 00:13:44.906 A:middle
We're always using the, kind of,

00:13:44.906 --> 00:13:46.026 A:middle
trajectories of everything

00:13:46.026 --> 00:13:47.546 A:middle
that's happening in the world to

00:13:47.546 --> 00:13:48.796 A:middle
predict the next few steps of

00:13:48.796 --> 00:13:49.296 A:middle
emotion.

00:13:50.316 --> 00:13:52.016 A:middle
So, we think it's great when an

00:13:52.046 --> 00:13:53.456 A:middle
interface plays into that

00:13:53.456 --> 00:13:53.906 A:middle
prediction.

00:13:54.556 --> 00:13:56.246 A:middle
So, if you have two states here,

00:13:56.966 --> 00:13:58.706 A:middle
initial state and a final state.

00:13:59.336 --> 00:14:00.446 A:middle
The object-- and you have an

00:13:59.336 --> 00:14:00.446 A:middle
The object-- and you have an

00:14:00.446 --> 00:14:01.996 A:middle
intermediate transition.

00:14:01.996 --> 00:14:03.746 A:middle
The object should transition

00:14:04.006 --> 00:14:05.586 A:middle
smoothly between these two

00:14:05.586 --> 00:14:07.176 A:middle
states in a way that it grows

00:14:07.176 --> 00:14:08.416 A:middle
from the initial state to the

00:14:08.536 --> 00:14:10.086 A:middle
final state, whether it's

00:14:10.086 --> 00:14:10.926 A:middle
through a gesture or an

00:14:10.926 --> 00:14:11.396 A:middle
animation.

00:14:12.666 --> 00:14:13.856 A:middle
So, good example is Control

00:14:13.856 --> 00:14:14.486 A:middle
Center actually.

00:14:15.206 --> 00:14:16.476 A:middle
We have these modules here in

00:14:16.476 --> 00:14:17.516 A:middle
Control Center, where as you

00:14:17.636 --> 00:14:19.286 A:middle
press they grow up and out

00:14:19.516 --> 00:14:21.166 A:middle
towards your finger in the

00:14:21.166 --> 00:14:22.696 A:middle
direction of the final state,

00:14:22.696 --> 00:14:25.226 A:middle
where it actually finally just

00:14:26.056 --> 00:14:26.426 A:middle
pops open.

00:14:26.566 --> 00:14:27.596 A:middle
So, that's hinting.

00:14:28.216 --> 00:14:29.586 A:middle
It makes the gestures feel

00:14:29.586 --> 00:14:33.626 A:middle
expected, and predictable.

00:14:33.626 --> 00:14:35.646 A:middle
Now, the next important

00:14:35.646 --> 00:14:37.556 A:middle
principle is to keep touch

00:14:37.606 --> 00:14:38.786 A:middle
interactions lightweight.

00:14:39.546 --> 00:14:40.526 A:middle
You know the lightness of

00:14:40.526 --> 00:14:41.836 A:middle
multitouch is one of the most

00:14:41.946 --> 00:14:43.406 A:middle
underrated aspects of it, I

00:14:43.496 --> 00:14:43.686 A:middle
think.

00:14:44.046 --> 00:14:46.386 A:middle
It enables the airy swipes and

00:14:46.386 --> 00:14:48.576 A:middle
scrolls, and all the taps and

00:14:48.576 --> 00:14:49.646 A:middle
stuff that we're all used to.

00:14:49.646 --> 00:14:51.236 A:middle
It's all super lightweight.

00:14:51.736 --> 00:14:53.876 A:middle
But, we also want to amplify

00:14:53.876 --> 00:14:54.436 A:middle
their motion.

00:14:54.926 --> 00:14:56.726 A:middle
You want to take a small input

00:14:56.726 --> 00:14:58.566 A:middle
and make a big output, to give

00:14:58.566 --> 00:15:00.336 A:middle
that satisfying feeling of

00:14:58.566 --> 00:15:00.336 A:middle
that satisfying feeling of

00:15:00.336 --> 00:15:01.656 A:middle
moving or throwing something and

00:15:01.656 --> 00:15:03.066 A:middle
having a magnified result.

00:15:03.096 --> 00:15:05.416 A:middle
So, how does this apply to our

00:15:05.416 --> 00:15:06.006 A:middle
interfaces?

00:15:06.086 --> 00:15:07.816 A:middle
Well, it starts with a short

00:15:07.876 --> 00:15:08.476 A:middle
interaction.

00:15:09.226 --> 00:15:10.416 A:middle
A short, lightweight

00:15:10.416 --> 00:15:11.016 A:middle
interaction.

00:15:11.856 --> 00:15:14.256 A:middle
And, we use all our sensors, all

00:15:14.256 --> 00:15:15.766 A:middle
our technology, to understand as

00:15:15.766 --> 00:15:16.586 A:middle
much about it.

00:15:17.096 --> 00:15:18.956 A:middle
To, sort of, generate a profile

00:15:18.956 --> 00:15:21.026 A:middle
of energy and momentum contained

00:15:21.026 --> 00:15:21.836 A:middle
within the gesture.

00:15:23.306 --> 00:15:24.426 A:middle
Using everything we know,

00:15:24.426 --> 00:15:26.256 A:middle
including position, velocity,

00:15:26.416 --> 00:15:28.116 A:middle
speed, force, everything we know

00:15:28.116 --> 00:15:30.566 A:middle
about it to generate a kind of,

00:15:30.566 --> 00:15:32.366 A:middle
inertial profile of this

00:15:32.366 --> 00:15:32.746 A:middle
gesture.

00:15:32.746 --> 00:15:34.506 A:middle
And then we take that, and

00:15:34.506 --> 00:15:37.406 A:middle
generate an amplified extension

00:15:37.406 --> 00:15:37.986 A:middle
of your movement.

00:15:37.986 --> 00:15:39.266 A:middle
It still feels like an extension

00:15:39.266 --> 00:15:39.556 A:middle
of you.

00:15:40.146 --> 00:15:41.696 A:middle
So, you get that satisfying

00:15:41.926 --> 00:15:43.666 A:middle
result with a light interaction.

00:15:45.156 --> 00:15:46.936 A:middle
So, a good example of this is

00:15:46.936 --> 00:15:47.876 A:middle
scrolling, actually.

00:15:47.876 --> 00:15:49.756 A:middle
Your finger's only onscreen for

00:15:49.836 --> 00:15:51.876 A:middle
a brief amount of time, but the

00:15:51.876 --> 00:15:53.496 A:middle
system is preserving all your

00:15:53.576 --> 00:15:54.926 A:middle
energy and momentum, and

00:15:54.986 --> 00:15:56.466 A:middle
gracefully transferring it into

00:15:56.466 --> 00:15:57.066 A:middle
the interface.

00:15:58.276 --> 00:15:59.506 A:middle
So, what if it didn't have this?

00:16:00.566 --> 00:16:02.566 A:middle
Those same swipes, well, they

00:16:02.566 --> 00:16:03.526 A:middle
wouldn't get you very far.

00:16:04.416 --> 00:16:07.946 A:middle
And, in order to scroll, you'd

00:16:07.946 --> 00:16:09.816 A:middle
have to do these long, laborious

00:16:09.946 --> 00:16:11.766 A:middle
swipes that would require a lot

00:16:11.766 --> 00:16:12.686 A:middle
more manual input.

00:16:12.686 --> 00:16:14.616 A:middle
It would be a huge pain to use.

00:16:15.816 --> 00:16:17.196 A:middle
Another good example of this is

00:16:17.296 --> 00:16:18.326 A:middle
swipe to go home.

00:16:19.076 --> 00:16:20.026 A:middle
The amount of time that your

00:16:20.026 --> 00:16:22.026 A:middle
finger's onscreen is very light.

00:16:22.736 --> 00:16:26.016 A:middle
And, it's-- ends up making it a

00:16:26.016 --> 00:16:27.656 A:middle
much more liquid and lightweight

00:16:27.686 --> 00:16:29.466 A:middle
gesture that still feels native

00:16:29.466 --> 00:16:30.706 A:middle
to the medium of multitouch.

00:16:31.506 --> 00:16:32.726 A:middle
While still being able to reuse

00:16:32.726 --> 00:16:33.976 A:middle
a lot of your muscle memory from

00:16:33.976 --> 00:16:35.346 A:middle
a button, because you move your

00:16:35.346 --> 00:16:36.676 A:middle
finger down on the screen, and

00:16:36.676 --> 00:16:37.686 A:middle
back up to the springboard.

00:16:38.306 --> 00:16:43.336 A:middle
And, it's not just swipes, it's

00:16:43.376 --> 00:16:44.446 A:middle
taps too.

00:16:44.886 --> 00:16:46.166 A:middle
It's important for an interface

00:16:46.166 --> 00:16:48.186 A:middle
to respond satisfyingly to every

00:16:48.186 --> 00:16:48.746 A:middle
interaction.

00:16:49.136 --> 00:16:50.416 A:middle
The interface is signaling to

00:16:50.416 --> 00:16:51.886 A:middle
you that it understood you.

00:16:52.336 --> 00:16:53.676 A:middle
It's so important for the

00:16:53.676 --> 00:16:55.096 A:middle
interface to feel alive and

00:16:55.096 --> 00:16:55.816 A:middle
connected to you.

00:16:56.916 --> 00:16:57.956 A:middle
So, that's the topic of

00:16:57.956 --> 00:16:58.886 A:middle
lightweightness and

00:16:58.946 --> 00:16:59.766 A:middle
amplification.

00:17:01.596 --> 00:17:03.246 A:middle
The next one is called

00:17:03.416 --> 00:17:04.006 A:middle
rubberbanding.

00:17:05.066 --> 00:17:07.156 A:middle
It means we're softly indicating

00:17:07.156 --> 00:17:08.665 A:middle
boundaries of the interface.

00:17:08.665 --> 00:17:12.296 A:middle
So, in this example, the

00:17:12.296 --> 00:17:14.215 A:middle
interface is gradually and

00:17:14.296 --> 00:17:15.626 A:middle
softly letting you know that

00:17:15.626 --> 00:17:16.266 A:middle
there's nothing there.

00:17:16.266 --> 00:17:17.346 A:middle
And, it's tracking you

00:17:17.425 --> 00:17:17.796 A:middle
throughout.

00:17:18.086 --> 00:17:19.266 A:middle
It's always letting you know

00:17:19.266 --> 00:17:20.165 A:middle
that it's understanding you.

00:17:21.016 --> 00:17:22.026 A:middle
What happens if you didn't do

00:17:22.026 --> 00:17:22.246 A:middle
that?

00:17:22.246 --> 00:17:23.846 A:middle
Well, it would feel like this.

00:17:23.846 --> 00:17:25.106 A:middle
It would feel super harsh and

00:17:25.106 --> 00:17:25.726 A:middle
disconcerting.

00:17:25.726 --> 00:17:27.126 A:middle
You kind of hit a wall there.

00:17:27.126 --> 00:17:28.326 A:middle
It would feel broken, right?

00:17:28.776 --> 00:17:29.976 A:middle
And, you actually wouldn't know

00:17:29.976 --> 00:17:31.476 A:middle
the difference between a frozen

00:17:31.476 --> 00:17:33.076 A:middle
phone, and phone that's just at

00:17:33.076 --> 00:17:34.046 A:middle
the top of the edge of the

00:17:34.046 --> 00:17:34.696 A:middle
screen, right?

00:17:34.786 --> 00:17:36.406 A:middle
So, it's really important that

00:17:36.406 --> 00:17:37.456 A:middle
it's always telling you that

00:17:37.456 --> 00:17:38.346 A:middle
you've reached the edge.

00:17:38.736 --> 00:17:41.706 A:middle
And, this applies to

00:17:41.706 --> 00:17:42.666 A:middle
transitions, too.

00:17:42.666 --> 00:17:43.736 A:middle
It's not just about when you hit

00:17:43.736 --> 00:17:45.086 A:middle
the edge, it's also when you

00:17:45.086 --> 00:17:46.836 A:middle
hand off from one thing to

00:17:46.836 --> 00:17:47.466 A:middle
another thing.

00:17:47.846 --> 00:17:50.926 A:middle
Tracking. So, a good example of

00:17:50.926 --> 00:17:53.026 A:middle
this is when you transition from

00:17:53.026 --> 00:17:54.366 A:middle
sliding up the dock to sliding

00:17:54.366 --> 00:17:54.876 A:middle
up the app.

00:17:55.566 --> 00:17:56.926 A:middle
It doesn't just hit a wall, and

00:17:56.926 --> 00:17:58.006 A:middle
one thing stops tracking, and

00:17:58.006 --> 00:17:59.196 A:middle
then the other thing takes over.

00:17:59.536 --> 00:18:01.466 A:middle
They both smoothly hand off in

00:17:59.536 --> 00:18:01.466 A:middle
They both smoothly hand off in

00:18:01.526 --> 00:18:04.026 A:middle
smooth curves, so that you don't

00:18:04.026 --> 00:18:06.166 A:middle
feel like there's this harsh

00:18:06.166 --> 00:18:07.696 A:middle
moment where you hand off from

00:18:07.696 --> 00:18:10.146 A:middle
one thing to another.

00:18:10.146 --> 00:18:12.236 A:middle
Next one is to design smooth

00:18:12.236 --> 00:18:13.216 A:middle
frames of motion.

00:18:14.546 --> 00:18:16.166 A:middle
So, imagine I have a little

00:18:16.666 --> 00:18:18.206 A:middle
object here moving up and down.

00:18:18.206 --> 00:18:18.936 A:middle
It's very simple.

00:18:19.636 --> 00:18:22.396 A:middle
But, we all know this object is

00:18:22.396 --> 00:18:23.626 A:middle
not really moving, right?

00:18:24.316 --> 00:18:25.456 A:middle
We're all just having the

00:18:25.456 --> 00:18:26.676 A:middle
perception of it moving.

00:18:26.676 --> 00:18:27.536 A:middle
Because we're seeing a bunch of

00:18:27.636 --> 00:18:29.466 A:middle
frames on the screen all at

00:18:29.466 --> 00:18:31.456 A:middle
once, and it's giving us the

00:18:31.456 --> 00:18:32.476 A:middle
illusion of it moving.

00:18:33.096 --> 00:18:33.916 A:middle
So, if we took all of those

00:18:33.916 --> 00:18:35.306 A:middle
frames of motion, and kind of,

00:18:35.306 --> 00:18:36.176 A:middle
spread them out here.

00:18:36.176 --> 00:18:37.806 A:middle
And we see the ball's in motion

00:18:37.806 --> 00:18:40.356 A:middle
over time, the thing that we're

00:18:40.356 --> 00:18:42.746 A:middle
concerned about is right around

00:18:42.746 --> 00:18:44.566 A:middle
here, where there's too much

00:18:44.566 --> 00:18:46.686 A:middle
visual change between the

00:18:47.176 --> 00:18:48.246 A:middle
adjacent frames.

00:18:48.626 --> 00:18:50.846 A:middle
This is when the perception of

00:18:50.846 --> 00:18:52.266 A:middle
the interface becomes a little

00:18:52.336 --> 00:18:52.866 A:middle
choppy.

00:18:53.326 --> 00:18:54.786 A:middle
You get this visual strobing.

00:18:55.796 --> 00:18:57.246 A:middle
And, this is because the

00:18:57.246 --> 00:18:58.336 A:middle
difference between the two

00:18:58.456 --> 00:18:59.776 A:middle
frames is too much.

00:19:00.966 --> 00:19:02.736 A:middle
And, it strobes against your

00:19:02.736 --> 00:19:03.626 A:middle
vision, so.

00:19:03.626 --> 00:19:04.576 A:middle
Here's an example of where you

00:19:04.576 --> 00:19:06.656 A:middle
have two things both moving at

00:19:06.656 --> 00:19:07.766 A:middle
30 frames per second.

00:19:08.266 --> 00:19:09.276 A:middle
But the one on the left looks a

00:19:09.356 --> 00:19:10.596 A:middle
bit smoother than the one on the

00:19:10.596 --> 00:19:11.476 A:middle
right, because the one on the

00:19:11.476 --> 00:19:14.036 A:middle
right is moving so fast, that

00:19:14.606 --> 00:19:15.336 A:middle
it's strobing.

00:19:15.416 --> 00:19:19.086 A:middle
My perception of vision is, kind

00:19:19.196 --> 00:19:19.946 A:middle
of, breaking down.

00:19:19.946 --> 00:19:21.806 A:middle
I don't believe that it's moving

00:19:21.806 --> 00:19:22.676 A:middle
smoothly any more.

00:19:23.566 --> 00:19:24.896 A:middle
So, the important thing to take

00:19:24.896 --> 00:19:26.446 A:middle
away is that it's not just about

00:19:26.516 --> 00:19:27.016 A:middle
framerate.

00:19:27.556 --> 00:19:28.876 A:middle
It's what's in the frames.

00:19:29.746 --> 00:19:31.426 A:middle
So, we're kind of limited by the

00:19:31.466 --> 00:19:32.956 A:middle
framerate, and how fast we can

00:19:32.956 --> 00:19:34.736 A:middle
move and still preserve a smooth

00:19:34.736 --> 00:19:35.186 A:middle
motion.

00:19:36.036 --> 00:19:37.806 A:middle
So, this one's in 30 frames per

00:19:37.806 --> 00:19:38.216 A:middle
second.

00:19:38.526 --> 00:19:40.016 A:middle
If we move it up to 60 frames

00:19:40.016 --> 00:19:42.036 A:middle
per second, you can see that we

00:19:42.036 --> 00:19:43.286 A:middle
can actually go a little bit

00:19:43.286 --> 00:19:45.486 A:middle
faster, and still preserve

00:19:45.576 --> 00:19:46.406 A:middle
smooth motion.

00:19:46.606 --> 00:19:47.776 A:middle
We can do faster movement

00:19:47.776 --> 00:19:48.586 A:middle
without strobing.

00:19:49.556 --> 00:19:50.736 A:middle
And, there's addition tricks we

00:19:50.736 --> 00:19:51.726 A:middle
can do too, we can do things

00:19:51.726 --> 00:19:52.556 A:middle
like motion blur.

00:19:52.556 --> 00:19:55.696 A:middle
Motion blur basically bakes in

00:19:55.696 --> 00:19:57.476 A:middle
more information in each frame

00:19:57.476 --> 00:19:59.276 A:middle
about the movement, like the way

00:19:59.276 --> 00:20:00.406 A:middle
your eyes work, and the way a

00:19:59.276 --> 00:20:00.406 A:middle
your eyes work, and the way a

00:20:00.406 --> 00:20:01.086 A:middle
camera works.

00:20:02.256 --> 00:20:03.316 A:middle
And you can also do-- take a

00:20:03.356 --> 00:20:05.396 A:middle
page from 2D animation and video

00:20:05.396 --> 00:20:07.026 A:middle
games by stretching, this-- this

00:20:07.026 --> 00:20:07.786 A:middle
technique called motion

00:20:07.786 --> 00:20:09.536 A:middle
stretching stretches the content

00:20:09.536 --> 00:20:12.376 A:middle
in each frame to provide this

00:20:12.376 --> 00:20:14.876 A:middle
elastic look as it moves with

00:20:14.876 --> 00:20:15.466 A:middle
velocity.

00:20:16.126 --> 00:20:19.246 A:middle
And so, in motion, it kind of

00:20:19.246 --> 00:20:20.086 A:middle
looks like this.

00:20:20.746 --> 00:20:22.126 A:middle
So, each of the different

00:20:22.126 --> 00:20:23.866 A:middle
techniques, kind of, tries to

00:20:23.866 --> 00:20:26.556 A:middle
encode more information visually

00:20:26.776 --> 00:20:28.466 A:middle
about what's going on in the

00:20:28.466 --> 00:20:28.896 A:middle
motion.

00:20:29.546 --> 00:20:30.386 A:middle
And, I want to focus a little

00:20:30.386 --> 00:20:31.286 A:middle
bit on this last one here,

00:20:31.286 --> 00:20:32.906 A:middle
motion stretching, because we do

00:20:32.906 --> 00:20:34.206 A:middle
this on iPhone 10, actually.

00:20:34.876 --> 00:20:36.136 A:middle
You know, when you launch an

00:20:36.136 --> 00:20:39.066 A:middle
app, the icon elastically

00:20:39.066 --> 00:20:40.606 A:middle
stretches down to become the app

00:20:41.076 --> 00:20:41.636 A:middle
as it opens.

00:20:42.366 --> 00:20:43.726 A:middle
And, it stretches up in the

00:20:43.726 --> 00:20:45.096 A:middle
opposite direction as you close

00:20:45.096 --> 00:20:45.556 A:middle
the app.

00:20:45.946 --> 00:20:46.876 A:middle
To give you that little bit

00:20:46.876 --> 00:20:48.486 A:middle
extra information between each

00:20:48.486 --> 00:20:49.786 A:middle
frame of motion to make it a

00:20:49.786 --> 00:20:53.366 A:middle
little bit smoother-looking.

00:20:53.366 --> 00:20:55.356 A:middle
Lastly, we want to work with

00:20:55.396 --> 00:20:57.546 A:middle
behavior rather than animation.

00:20:58.226 --> 00:20:59.226 A:middle
You know, things in the real

00:20:59.226 --> 00:21:00.836 A:middle
world are always in a state of

00:20:59.226 --> 00:21:00.836 A:middle
world are always in a state of

00:21:00.836 --> 00:21:02.006 A:middle
dynamic motion, and they're

00:21:02.006 --> 00:21:03.516 A:middle
always being influenced by you.

00:21:03.886 --> 00:21:05.316 A:middle
They don't really work like

00:21:05.356 --> 00:21:06.886 A:middle
animations in the animation

00:21:06.936 --> 00:21:07.366 A:middle
sense, right?

00:21:07.366 --> 00:21:09.336 A:middle
There's no animation curve

00:21:09.336 --> 00:21:10.786 A:middle
prescribed by real life.

00:21:11.406 --> 00:21:12.256 A:middle
So, we want to think about

00:21:12.256 --> 00:21:13.816 A:middle
animation and behavior more as a

00:21:13.866 --> 00:21:15.216 A:middle
conversation between you and the

00:21:15.216 --> 00:21:15.626 A:middle
object.

00:21:15.956 --> 00:21:17.376 A:middle
Not prescribed by the interface.

00:21:17.956 --> 00:21:20.226 A:middle
So, to move away from static

00:21:20.296 --> 00:21:21.436 A:middle
things transitioning into

00:21:21.436 --> 00:21:22.926 A:middle
animated things, instead think

00:21:22.956 --> 00:21:23.806 A:middle
about behavior.

00:21:24.506 --> 00:21:26.206 A:middle
So, Nathan's about to dive deep

00:21:26.206 --> 00:21:26.826 A:middle
